You&#39;re firing the `onListen(items)` before you&#39;ve actually checked the existence. Any code that depends on data from the database must be **inside** the callback that fires when that data is available.

Since you want to perform multiple checks, consider using a counter to check whether all of them completed:

    firestoreInstance.collection(&quot;users&quot;)
        .addSnapshotListener { querySnapshot, firebaseFirestoreException -&gt;
            if(firebaseFirestoreException !=null){
                return@addSnapshotListener
            }

            val count = 0

            val items = mutableListOf&lt;Item&gt;()
            querySnapshot?.documents?.forEach {
                firestoreInstance.collection(&quot;users&quot;)
                    .document(it.id).collection(&quot;engagedChatChannels&quot;).get()
                    .continueWith { result-&gt;
                        if(result.result!!.size() &gt; 0)
                            items.add(
                                UserItem(
                                    it.toObject(User::class.java)!!,
                                    it.id,
                                    0,
                                    context
                                )
                            )
                        }
                        count = count + 1
                        if (count == querySnapshot?.documents?.size) {
                            onListen(items)
                        }
                    }
        }

Note that I didn&#39;t run the above code, so it may contain syntax errors. However I hope the flow is clear, with both the `onListen` call being inside the callback, and the counter used to check if all subcollection checks were done.

---

