    const order = [&#39;31&#39;, &#39;22&#39;];
    const mapper = new Map(order.map((v, i) =&gt; [parseInt(v), i + 1]))

    const sorted = data.sort((a, b) =&gt; (
      (mapper.get(a.id) || Infinity) - (mapper.get(b.id) || Infinity)
    ));

    console.log(sorted)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

The problem is because of id `22`. It does not exist in `order` array and `indexOf` function return `-1` for this id. It means the `top priority`, so it appears in the first place of result array.
You should handle ids that do not exist in the `order` array.
For example (for sorting) you can do as below:

    const sorted = data.sort((a, b) =&gt; {
        let aindex = order.indexOf(a.id);
        let bindex = order.indexOf(b.id);
        if(aindex === -1) return 1;
        if(bindex === -1) return -1;
        return aindex  - bindex;
    });

